Explore More Semantic Landmark Element Options

07

We've learned a lot about headings and landmarks, but there are other ways to add semantic structure to our pages.

For example, if you use an unordered list (the ul tag) for links, a screen reader will read out a count like “Link one of four”. This provides additional information to the user.

Tables are also great for adding semantic structure. We’ll dig in further when we work with our date picker.

Bookmark MDN’s elements reference, as it’s a great starting point for suggestions on which elements to choose depending on the situation.

For example, you might consider the <menu> tag would be better than the <ul> depending on your situation. But you would need to test it.

I will caution that MDN and other docs aren’t always on top of current accessibility gotchas, so it is important to do your own testing to ensure pages work as expected with Assistive Technology.
